text:
When warm applause from an open-hearted crowd
Confers that truest prize—renown unbowed;
When here your grace becomes the player’s share,
And private self is kept in memory’s care;
What soul, so numb to sacred Virtue’s flame,
Fails to surge with thanks, a pulse no art can tame?

source_text:
When, by a generous Public’s kind acclaim,
That dearest meed is granted—honest fame;
Waen here your favour is the actor’s lot,
Nor even the man in private life forgot;
What breast so dead to heavenly Virtue’s glow,
But heaves impassion’d with the grateful throe?

text:
O streams, deep woods, high peaks, and fields so wide!
My merry songs you’ve often heard with pride;
Yet now, what’s left for me to sing beside
But sorrow’s rhyme;
And from my eyes the falling rain will slide
Through all my time.

source_text:
O rivers, forests, hills, and plains!
Oft have ye heard my canty strains;
But now, what else for me remains
But tales of woe;
And frae my een the drapping rains
Maun ever flow.

text:
Could she have foreseen this end;
Could some bright herald of joy ascend
That far-off, silent hill;
Had rapture not moved at such a crawl, —
Who can say this yielded face, after all,
Might not be radiant still?

source_text:
Could she have guessed that it would be;
Could but a crier of the glee
Have climbed the distant hill;
Had not the bliss so slow a pace, --
Who knows but this surrendered face
Were undefeated still?

text:
Twenty-eight young men wade into the surf,  
Twenty-eight young men, their laughter easy and warm;  
Twenty-eight years of a woman’s life, and all of it so alone.

source_text:
Twenty-eight young men bathe by the shore,
Twenty-eight young men and all so friendly;
Twenty-eight years of womanly life and all so lonesome.

text:
I know not which blooms lie scattered at my feet,
Nor what faint fragrance drifts among the limbs,
Yet, in this scented gloom, I sense each sweet
The timely season lavishes and brims
On meadow, copse, and wild fruit-laden tree;
Pale hawthorn, and the hedgerow eglantine;
Quick-fading violets shrouded deep in leaves;
And mid-May’s firstborn, see—
The budding musk-rose, drenched in dewy wine,
Where droning flies will throng on summer eves.

source_text:
I cannot see what flowers are at my feet,
Nor what soft incense hangs upon the boughs,
But, in embalmed darkness, guess each sweet
Wherewith the seasonable month endows
The grass, the thicket, and the fruit-tree wild;
White hawthorn, and the pastoral eglantine;
Fast fading violets cover'd up in leaves;
And mid-May's eldest child,
The coming musk-rose, full of dewy wine,
The murmurous haunt of flies on summer eves.

Dear mother, dear mother, the Church is cold;
But the Alehouse is healthy, and pleasant, and warm.
Besides, I can tell where I am used well;
Such usage in heaven will never do well.

Soon my Angel came again;
I was armed, he came in vain;
For the time of youth was fled,
And grey hairs were on my head.

text:
I’d humbly, gladly drop a clue,  
That one pound sterling I sorely rue;  
If with the lass you sent it through,  
’Twould be a grace;  
And while my heart with life-blood grew,  
I’d hold its place.

source_text:
I modestly fu’ fain wad hint it,
That One—pound—one, I sairly want it;
If wi’ the hizzie down ye sent it,
It would be kind;
And while my heart wi’ life-blood dunted,
I’d bear’t in mind.

Therefore they watch'd a time when they might sift
This hidden whim; and long they watch'd in vain;
For seldom did she go to chapel-shrift,
And seldom felt she any hunger-pain;
And when she left, she hurried back, as swift
As bird on wing to breast its eggs again;
And, patient, as a hen-bird, sat her there
Beside her Basil, weeping through her hair.

text:
In a small chamber I hold images hung, it is no steady chamber,  
It curves, barely a handspan from edge to edge;  
Still, see—it contains the whole pageant of the world, every remembrance!  
Here, the living panels, and here, the assemblies of the dead;  
Here—do you recognize this?—the guide himself,  
With lifted hand he gestures toward the lavish scenes.

source_text:
In a little house keep I pictures suspended, it is not a fix’d house,
It is round, it is only a few inches from one side to the other;
Yet behold, it has room for all the shows of the world, all memories!
Here the tableaus of life, and here the groupings of death;
Here, do you know this? this is cicerone himself,
With finger rais’d he points to the prodigal pictures.

text:
Shame and pride gave rise to man and woman,
Breathed into dawn, by dusk undone;
Yet mercy turned their end to rest;
They woke to labor, grieved, and bled.

source_text:
The sexes sprung from shame and pride,
Blowed in the morn, in evening died;
But mercy changed death into sleep;
The sexes rose to work and weep.
